p2
VTreat of music and dance
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe much-awaited Golden Jubilee of Ghantasala Venkateswara Rao Government College of Music, Vijayawada, was celebrated for five days at Gokaraju Laila Gangaraju Kala Vedika situated on the spacious grounds of the college.&#160;The celebrations, though delayed by an year, was memorable. The college old students association&#160;&#160;was also part of the functions.&#160;The cultural programmes began with an excellently staged dance drama Mahishasura Mardini&#160;presented by the troupe from Sarada Kalakshetra Centre, Hyderabad.&#160;The Kuchipudi dance drama was effectively choreographed by Ajay Srinivasa Chakravarthy and Ghantasala Pavan Kumar.&#160;Melody on mandolinFollowing this, reputed mandolin artiste U.P. Raju and his wife-disciple Nagamani Raju gave a pleasing concert, beginning with the popular item Navaraga Malika. Vandeham Jagadvallabham, an Annamayya keertana, was played in the concert with a brief alapana and crisp kalpana swaras. &#160;&#160;&#160;Preceding the mandolin concert there was a brief welcome dance Swarnotsava Nrityam choreographed by Ch. Ajaykumar, a staff member of the college.&#160;&#160;The third day's sitar concert by Prof. Himasagar Chakravarthi was mediocre but not lacking in sruti alignment. Himasagar played two khyaals in Behag and Desh treating the ragas with vilambit and drut layas.&#160;&#160;This was followed by the rendition of Annamacharya keertanas by singer Garimella Balakrishna Prasad. The highlights of his concert were Tiro Tiro Javarala (Gambhiranata), Kalasapuramu kada (Vasanta) and Vachenu Alamelumanga (Hindola).&#160;The concert included Prasad's own composition in praise of Annamacharya in chakravakam.&#160;Balakrishna Prasad and was ably supported on violin by P. Nageswara Rao and on mridangam by D. Sumathi Ramamohana Rao.A brilliant dance performance by Kumari Nadiya of Nellore was featured first the next day.&#160;The first item in Nadiya's performance was Milita Sangeetam, an innovatively choreographed number.&#160;&#160;Nadiya's performance was followed by a thrilling instrumental ensemble led by D. Srinivas, a well known veena artiste from Hyderabad.&#160;Other artistes in the group were V. Nagaraju (flute), M. Surya Deepti (violin), M.L.N. Raju (mridangam) M. Haribabu (ghatam) and T. Lakshmi Shanker (morsing).&#160;With superb coordination, the group played Natakuranji varnam Mahaganapathim in Nata, Ganamurthe in the melakartha raga Ganamurthi and Nagumomu in Abheri.&#160;&#160;There was never a dull moment in the concert.The last day's programme began with brief but enjoyable dances by K. Kavya and T. Srisavya of Anantapur.&#160;Natyacharya Patnam Sivaprasad conducted the nattuvangam efficiently. The last programme of the five-day fete was a lilting vocal concert by Swathi Srikrishna of Chennai.&#160;&#160;&#160;Swathi pleasingly rendered Swathi Thirunal's Bhuvaneswariya in this raga. The main item Prakkala Nilabadi in kharaharapriya was pleasingly rendered by the singer with fine treat of raga, niraval and kalpana swaras. Violin accompanist B.V. Durgabhavani, a staff artiste of Akashvani, made her presence felt with melodious versions of Mohanakalyani and Kharaharapriya.&#160;I. Pinakapani of Nellore supported the singer excellently on the mridangam and his tani spoke volumes of his rhythmic expertise.&#160;Swathi Srikrishna concluded with an abhang of St. Tukaram, Emisetura Linga, a tatvam and a thillana in Revati.
